### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. Choices:  A: communication B: suffering C: pain D: laughter E: embarrassment<n>Output:		 Pain<n><n>Input: A boy and a girl stand facing each other, with their backs touching. If the sum of their heights is one meter, and the girl is twice as tall as the boy, how tall is the boy?<n>Output:  0.5 meters<n><n>Input: 5/6+3/6-1/6+2/6+9/6<n><n>Output: 7/6<n><n>Input: 2 5/6 - 9/6<n><n>Input:-2^((n-1)/2)+3<n><n>Output:  10<n><n>#### Solution:Input:<n><n>How many less?<n><n>If you had nine puppies, then four less means you have five puppies. Nine - five =four. <n><n>If you had eleven puppies, then eleven - four means you have seven puppies. Eleven - four = seven. If you had twelve puppies, then twelve - seven means you have five pups. Twelve - seven = five puppies.<n><n>If you had fifteen puppies, then fifteen - five = ten puppies. Fifteen - five = ten pups.<n><n>If you have two puppy names then add one minus the number of puppies.<n>Puppy name is Schnauzer?<n>If you had eleven Schnauzers, and five less, then we subtract five from eleven: 5 - 5 = 0. The answer is 0. <n>If you have four puppy names then add two minus the number of puppy names, then subtract one.<n><n><n>How many pups?<n><n>If you have fifteen puppies, and then five more, then we added five to fifteen: Fifteen + five. The answer is twenty. If you have fourteen schnauzer puppies and two more, then we added two to fourteen: Fourteen + two. The answer is sixteen. You must subtract sixteen from sixteen. Sixteen - sixteen = zero.<n><n>If you're starting with fifteen schnauzer pups and three less would mean we subtract three from fifteen. The answer is twelve schnauzers.<n>

On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: 9<n><n>Input: Every hour past noon shadows from a building stretch an extra 5 feet, starting at zero at noon.  How long are the shadows from the building 6 hours past noon in inches?<n>Output: 360<n><n>Input:A wife asks a husband to stop being married to her, what is he likely to feel even with friends? Choices:  A: happiness B: pleasure C: happy D: grief E: isolation<n>Output:		A<n><n>Input: If you add 226 and 117 to find the sum of a number, you get 343.  After adding these two numbers, you then subtract the resulting number from the number itself, and you get a remainder of 10. What number are you adding?<n>Output: 100<n>

In the summer, 1.75  degrees is added for each day, but in the winter, 4.5 degrees is subtracted each day, for a total annual change of 3 degrees for each calendar day.  What is the average temperature in the summer in the city?<n>Output: 124<n><n>Input: Scalars are not suitable for describing how long 31 minutes plus 31 minutes is. This is because 31 minutes plus anything is 62 minutes. A vector provides a better means to compare quantities in this instance.  A vector is a <n>sequence of numbers. It describes quantity or direction.  It always has a length, called its magnitude.  A vector can be positive or negative. Every vector is described as the combination of two scalars: a magnitude and a direction.  There are only two possible ways of representing a vector: (1) with a magnitude and a direction, or (2) a magnitude and a direction angle. <n><n>To represent a vector, use one of the following:<n><n>• a pair of numbers—a magnitude and a direction vector representing an object’s position. <n><n>In this exercise, you will see the second option in the context of a flight to Denmark.  To compute it, you will need the function  atan2 (in the math package), which returns the angle made by a line segment defined by two<n>coordinates, starting from the coordinate line x = 1.0.<n><n>The following code snippet shows how to use the function. For each run, you will be presented with two  coordinate numbers from which to compute the direction angle of the flight.  <n> <n>  The second line in the example generates a vector representing the line 4  x = 2.0. Atan 2 returns the angle of that vector,  the number between 0 and 2. <n><n>  In the example, the vector 4 4 + x2 is projected onto the coordinate line x =   1.0.  The projection occurs from the point on that line nearest to 4 4 +x2. This projection is represented by  the y coordinate of  the vector. Its size is proportional to 4 4+x2 and has the direction angle atan2(x2, 4

There are 25 boys and 1 fewer girl. <n>

Then compile it and run.<n>```<n>class Human<n>	def initialize<n>		@name = "Lowry Cathy"<n>end<n>```<n>### Answer the following questions in your own words. The answers that follow are in red.<n><n>Question : In what situation would you use a new keyword?<n><n>Answer :  I would use a new keyword when writing instructions for a computer to run.<n><n>Question : What are the differences between an abstract class and a template class?<n><n>Answer : An abstract class is a class whose instances that is can only have a subclass. A template class can be any type of object and can also have subclasses.<n><n>### Question : What is a template in Python?<n><n>Answer : A template is a special method with a special syntax that is used to make templates.<n><n>### Answer :What is a data instance in Python?<n><n>A data instance is a single data item.<n>### Question:<n><n>What is a set in Python and how do you define it?<n><n>### Answer:<n><n>a set is an "immutable" collection of objects that we can store in a variable.  a variable that has a stored variable of type set is usually referred to as a set variable.  sets are an inexpensive and very convenient data structure in that they always hold the same values and we can "add" elements to the beginning of the set, but we can never "delete" from the set.  if we want to check if a set has a particular object in it, we can use the in function.  for both adding and looking up things we can use the function named add

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: 9<n><n>Input: Every hour past noon shadows from a building stretch an extra 5 feet, starting at zero at noon.  How long are the shadows from the building 6 hours past noon in inches?<n>Output: 360<n><n>Input:Dan said that getting in line was the best choice because it would lead to what? Choices:  A: being ordered B: less confusion C: boredom D: standing in line E: have to wait for<n>Output:		being ordered<n><n># Program:<n>class Solution:<n>    def calculateMinimumTime(self, time, time1, time2):<n>        """<n>        :type time: str<n>        :type time1: str<n>        :rtype: str<n>        """<n>        if time[0] not in '0329':<n>            return 'Sorry, invalid input'<n>        arr1=time.split('/',1);<n>        arr2=time1.split('/',1)<n>        arr3=time2.split('/',1 )<n>        res={};<n>        res[1]=0<n>        res[0]=int(arr1[0])+int(arr2[0])+int (arr3[0])<n>        if arr1[0]=='59':<n>            res[0]=(res[0]+60)%60<n>        for i in range(1,len(arr1)):<n>            if i not in res.keys():<n>                res[i]=arr1[i] + arr2[i] + arr3[i]<n>                res[i]=(res[i]+res[i-1])%60<n>                if res[i]==0:<n>                    res[i]=int(res[i])<n>                else:<n>                    res=str(225000*res[i])#convert to minutes<n>                    res=res[0]+int(res[1:3])<n>        if not res.get(3,0)==0:<n>            res=str(48 - res[0])+":"+str(2-res[1])#convert to hrs:mins<n>            return res <n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: 9<n><n>Input: Every hour past noon shadows from a building stretch an extra 5 feet, starting at zero at noon.  How long are the shadows from the building 6 hours past noon in inches?<n>Output: 360<n><n>Input:What does playing soccer for a long time lead to? Choices:  A: excitement B: fatigue C: anger D: hurting E: getting tired<n>Output:		C (anger-because soccer gets more aggravating and more frustrating as time goes on)<n><n>## **Solution:**<n><n>### Dobermans and Schnauzers<n><n><n>### Answer:<n><n>```python<n>def solve_question_dobbies_and_schnauzers(dbl):<n>    """<n>    :param dbl:<n>    :return:<n>    """<n><n>    return dbl - dbl % (-1,60 + 90 - 90)<n><n>```<n><n>### Answer :2<n><n>```python<n>import math<n><n>def solve_question(dbl):<n><n>    return math.ceil(dbl - (dbl - dbl % 45))<n><n>```<n><n><n>   <n><n><n>### Explanation :<n><n>```python<n><n>    S = 60 # number when 60 % m = 1<n>    E = 9 # number when 90 % m = 0<n><n>    dbl = int(input('Please enter the number of Dobermans :'))<n><n>    dbl_mod = dbl % -1<n>    dbl_sub_mod = dbl_mod - (dbl_mod - 20)<n>    newnum = dbl + dbl_mod<n>    n_times =  newnum % (E - S)<n>    if n_times == 0 or n_times == S: <n>        return(dbl-newnum)<n>    else:  <n>        return(dint)<n><n>```<n>        <n>### Answer : 3<n><n>```python<n>l = int(input("Please enter the number of doberman puppies :"))<n>s = l+1<n>u = (l / 60)<n>s = s - (s - (s * 60))<n>return s<n><n>```<n><n>   <n><n>### Exlanation :<n><n>```<n>Number can be divided by 60 if it is divisible by 15<n>Lemme go through the step of how to divide to see if it is divisible<n>If the remainder is 5 or 0, then you need to continue with 15, otherwise keep going by 15<n>If u (u1 and u2 are u1 +

Choices:  A: suicide B: overdosing C: sadness D: murder E: cyanide<n>Output:		B<n><n>Input: Five oranges are 20% more than three bananas. What fraction of a pound of oranges is three bananas?<n>Output: The correct answer is 1/5.<n><n>Input: How many chickens are currently alive on a farm of 40 chickens if 8 chickens die per week?<n>Output: The first chicken died after week 1 and there are 43 chickens left after week 4.<n><n>Input: There is a line of $100 bills totaling $10,000. Every three days, the line grows by two extra bills. How many new bills are in the line, and how many cents will they be worth exactly?<n>Output: There are 8 extra bills for an extra total of $200 if they are all $10 bills. The extra cents that they are worth is 13 cents each since they make a grand total of $280.<n>

")<n>except Exception as p:<n><n>print(p)<n>    <n>except e:<n><n>assert(True)

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: 9<n><n>Input: Every hour past noon shadows from a building stretch an extra 5 feet, starting at zero at noon.  How long are the shadows from the building 6 hours past noon in inches?<n>Output: 360<n><n>Input:what can years of playing tennis lead to? Choices:  A: tennis elbow B: proffesional player C: exercise D: victory E: becoming tired<n>Output:		  C<n><n>Input:what will an elephant be soon? Chosen from: A: mother B: father C: baby D: sister E: enemy<n>Output: B<n><n>Input: What is the second way to say what number of digits a number can have? Choices: A: A number of n digits B: A number of characters C: A number of symbols<n>Output: B<n>    <n>### solution:<n>Let's first solve part 1 using backtracking.<n><n>There are 5 choices (or possibilities) that we first check whether it satisfies the given criterias or not and for every choice that fails we remove them after check. In this case first of all we want to subtract 5 from the total number of doberman and then find the difference between the numbers of doberman and schnauzers so if the difference is greater than or equal to 5 we can make a match in this case.<n><n>The following shows how backtracking works:<n>```python<n>solution_1 = backtrack(["3 is greater than 5", "4 is greater than 5"])    <n>```<n><n>Now for part 2 (let's see what solution 2 gives us):<n>```python<n>soln = backtrack(["2 is an even number", "3 is an odd number"])    <n>        ```<n>When we tried to solve the 2nd one using backtracking we got nothing. What's wrong with the above code? backtracking is correct but why didn't we get what we intended to?<n>The reason that it didn't return anything is because of the criterias that were given in the beginning and this is shown by the fact that both part 1 and part 2 are all about integer number. So in order to get the solution on both cases we have to solve each one separately so we used backtracking but not for integer we used recursion.<n><n>Recursion is a technique of programming where a basic function calls itself. We can achieve this by using the'self' keyword. The following shows another try for part 1 <n><n>```python<n>sol5=recursiveFunction([("2 less than 4",1),("3 greater than 4",2),("4 less than 5",3),("5 is greater than 5/2",4),("6 is greater than 5","5")])<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Jordan caught 4 fish and Perry caught double what Jordan caught. On the way back to shore, the boat tipped over and they lost one-fourth of their total catch. How many fish remain?<n>Output: 9<n><n>Input: Every hour past noon shadows from a building stretch an extra 5 feet, starting at zero at noon.  How long are the shadows from the building 6 hours past noon in inches?<n>Output: 360<n><n>Input:There's a lot to reproducing, but it begins and end with new life by giving what? Choices:  A: overpopulation B: birth C: presents D: propagation E: fun<n>Output:		B<n><n>Input: You've been asked to pick a friend to be in a movie with you. Choose your friend by answering which of the following criteria is your criteria A: He/she is younger than you. B: He/she is older than you. C: He/she is taller than you. D: He/she is shorter than you. E: He/she has a better singing voice than you.<n>Output: C, D<n><n>### Solution<n>### <n>```python<n>class Solution:<n>    def solveMe(self, nums):<n>        count = 0<n>        for x in range(len(nums)):<n>            nums.append(0)<n>        for j in range(len(x))[1:]:<n>            for i in range(j+1,len(nums)):    <n>                if(nums[i] == 0 and nums[i-j+1] > 0):<n>                count += 1<n>                <n>                nums[i] = 1<n>        c = count<n>        return c<n>```<n><n><n>###  <n>

Choices:  A: show B: theatre C: hockey game D: movies E: event<n>Output:		C<n><n>Input:  A, E, T, H<n>Output: I<n><n>Input: 1,-3,2,-4,4,-2,1,-3,3,...<n>Output:1,-4,3,2,-3,3,-2<n><n><n><n><n>### Solution:<n><n>### A<n><n>$2X-3=20$<n><n>$\Rightarrow X=26$<n><n>### B<n><n>$\Rightarrow A+B=12+\frac{1}{2}(9+8+5)=22$<n><n>### C<n><n>$\Rightarrow 123=\frac{100}{15}$<n><n>### D<n><n>$10-3x-2+7=100$<n><n>$\frac{100+7-10-3x}{7-1}=3$<n><n>### E<n><n>$\Rightarrow \frac{6}{8}{4}+2=24$<n><n>$\Rightarrow A$<n><n>### F<n><n>$\Rightarrow 3240=9\times325$<n><n>$\Rightarrow 9712=$<n><n>### G<n><n>$C +1 = 1 + A-D$<n><n>$\Rightarrow B=11$<n><n>### H <n><n>First note, in this case the answer will be a negative number.<n><n>$0.125 = 12.50 \%$<n><n>$\Rightarrow K=0.01$<n><n>$\Rightarrow (0.5+0.15)\times0.1=1.65$<n><n>$\frac{-100}{5-5+1.65}$<n><n>$\Rightarrow G=-636$<n><n><n><n><n>

Choices:  A: dictionary B: wilderness C: fly D: underground E: colorado<n>Output:		 wilderness<n>![enter image description here](https://i.postimg.cc/SQSs4Y10/image.png)<n>#### C++ Code:<n><n>```cpp<n>bool check_answer(string& s) // Checks if string has correct answer<n>{<n>	if (! (s == "55")) {<n>		return false;<n><n><n>		for (int i = 0; i < 6; i++)<n>			if (s[i]!= '5') return false;<n><n><n><n><n>		return false;}<n>	<n><n>	return true;<n>}<n>int solution(string& s)<n>{<n>	int x = 0;<n>	int sum = 0;<n><n>	stringstream sstr(s);<n><n>	do {<n>		getline(sstr, s[x],'');<n>		x++;<n>	} while (check_answer(s));<n>	<n>	s.pop_back();<n>	s.pop();<n>	getline(s,'');<n><n><n>	for (int i=0; i < 10; i++)<n>	{	<n>		if (s.size() > i)<n>			sum += (int(s[i]) - 48);<n>	}		<n>	return sum;<n><n>}<n>```<n>

The result of the expression subtracting their number from Schnauzer number is just the number of Schanuzers.<n><n><n>![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/72442722/134089498-a71b3759-44f7-4852-8e9f-a562f2b5fd60.png)<n><n>In this expression, we first subtract 67 from total number of toothbrushes Dr Banks had then we subtract the 185 remaining from 330 to give the number of toothbrashes he gave away to his patient in the first month of the year. Then we subtract the toothbrushes he donated in month 2 from 67 of month 1 to get the number of tooth brashes for month 3. Subtract the first 2 months’ months’ number from the total to get the number of month 4 toothbrushes.(Dr Banks donated 40% of his total supply to his patients)<n><n><n>![image-3](https://user- images.githubusercontent.org/72447222/132363768-ae23e865-3d7f-4810-b173-1a33c432c60

Choices:  A: anger B: not boredom C: stress D: boredom E: anxiety<n>Output:		E<n><n>### Solution:<n>class Solution:<n>  def __init__(self):<n>    self.dict = {}<n>    <n>  def singleNumber(self, matrix):<n>    for i in range (0,len(matrix[0])):<n>      max = [i]+[str(i+1)]<n>      for j in range (0, len(matrix[0]))<n>      m = max[j]+matrix[j][:i]<n>      if self.dict.get(m,0)+1:<n>        if self.dict.keys() == []:<n>          self.dict[m]=1<n>        else:<n>          self.isSingle(i,j,self.dict.keys())<n>  <n>  def isSingle(self, i,j,keys): <n>    if i < len(keys):<n>      if keys[(i+1)] == matrix[i][j]+str(i+1):<n>        self.dict[matrix[i][j]+(str(i+1))] = 1<n>        return True<n>      else:<n>        return False<n>    <n><n><n>if __name__ == "__main__":<n>    testInst = Solution()<n>    data = [[1,3,4],[3,2,4],[1,5,9]]<n>    count = 0<n>    for i in matrix: <n>        for i2 in matrix[i]:<n>            count+=1<n>        if i==0 or i== 2:<n>        print (i2, count);<n>            pass<n>            if count == len(i):<n><n>        else:            <n><n>         data1 = [[1,2,1],[1,2,2]]<n>         print (testInst.singleNumber(data1))        <n>    input("hit any key to exit")<n>

Which hat is white? We then repeatedly compare the key we are looking for with the values in our range. If the key is less than either of our bounds, we increment the lower bound. If we hit the upper bound, we bail out. Otherwise we set the lower bound to the current midpoint and increment the upper bound, then repeat the process.<n><n>In pseudocode the binary search function we are implementing looks like this:<n><n>  <n>`def binary_search(a: list, key: int) -> bool:<n>    # return True if key found in a, False otherwise<n>    """<n>    Return True if key found in list a, False otherwise<n>    <n>    Preconditions<n>    a is a list of ints<n>    key is an element in the range of a<n>    If key is out of range of list a, return False<n>    """<n>    if key < low(a) or key > high(a):<n>      return False<n>  <n>    # get an exact middle value for list<n>    mid =

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. Choices:  A: outside B: vacation C: idle D: apartment E: neighborhood<n>Output:		Aptitude Tests (or Apartment): When I was hone, I was comfortable.<n><n>### Solution:This is a question,  The answer will not show the actual process<n><details><summary>View the process</summary><p><n><pre id="pre" style="line-height:1.6; text-align:justify; text-indent:30px; text-transform:capitalize;"><span style="color:#2a4987">Factor 1:</span> If the number of Dobernan puppies is 10,then there are 45 schnauzers in the world. <span style="color:#dc3912">Because,</span> There are five times of schnauzers. <span style="font-size:16px">If the number of Dobernans is 10,</span> the number of schnauzens are 10 × 5 = 50. <span style="line-height:#487094">And, 5 more in 90 than the total schnauzens.</span><n><br><n>We have to subtract one from the total schnauzen to give one number. <span style="italic">So,</span> the remaining schnaruers are 44. <span style="vertical-align:top">Factor 2:</span> So, if the total number of schnauzen is 44, <span style="vertical: top; font-size:17px">The total is equal to five plus the difference</span>.<n><br><n><span style="color:#4285f4">So,</span>, We need to find out the difference between the schnauzens and the dobernans. <span style="opacity: 1; line-height:1.2;">If the total is 5, we need to find out five minus two more from the total, <span style="color:red; text-decoration:underline; vertical-align:bottom;">Because 44 minus 20 is equal to 24.</span></span> <n><br><n>Let us see the steps:<n>1. 44 minus 5 = 39<n>2.

He measures the dog's height at 12 feet and adds 2 feet to that height, which equals 14 feet. By cutting back a large amount of the top of the dog's hair, the dog is now 13 feet tall and looks good. What is the mathematical relationship between the dog's height and the amount of hair shaved off to arrive at a height of 13 feet? (Note the original dog height is 12 feet. The hair is removed to bring it to 13 feet. The mathematical relationship is called the inverse variation.)Answer: Inverse variation (e.g., 8 feet for 10 feet) is a mathematical relationship where: If there is a change in the number of feet a dog is tall, the amount of hair cut is the inverse. Choices:  A: make music B: believe in god C: give speeches D: complete sentences E: build houses<n>Output:		 Answer D.  Give speech is an adjective, that is describing the verb  to give. Notice that the question is  "Which people are speech therapists?  " We want to select only the ones who are speech therapist. So if a person is giving speeches, they don't necessarily do it everyday so it cannot be C, and we don't need to believe in God. So the person must be a Speech Therapist which should be answer: D.<n><n>Input: Choose the sentence in which the plural subject agrees with the verb. Choices: A: The girls do their homework right. B: The girls do their work everyday C: The girls work hard D: The girls do their works<n>Output: Answer D.  The subject in this subject is "girls" and the verb is "do", so it must be plural.<n>Output: Answer B. The subject in this subject should be "them" and the verb is is "does" which means it should be singular.<n><n>Input: What is the plural form of "moose"? Choices:  A moose B moose C mooses D mooses<n>Output: Answer A.  The plural form of moose is mooses.<n><n>Output: Answer C. All 3 sentences are not correct since "we are" should be "were" since "is" is in the present tense.<n><n>Input: The plural verb forms of "be" are  A: I am B: I was C: I was D: I are<n>Output: Answer D, The answer is "I are", since the verb is I am and am is 3rd person plural. <n><n>Input: Which is the correct singular verb? Choices: A:  I am B:  I are C:  I is D:  I ams<n>Output: Answer A, Singular subjects takes singular verbs so the answer is I am. The other three are wrong.<n><n>Input: Which sentence is correct? Choices:  I am always honest A: B: C: D:  I am always honesty<n>Output: Answer A I am always honest.  Note, answer D has the wrong subject and the wrong end of the sentence.<n><n>Input: Find the word with a possessive apostrophe. Choices:  A. I

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Choices:  A: construction site B: cemetary C: building D: city E: archeological site<n>Output:		All of the answers are valid.<n><n>Input: A number x has even digits, a number y has odd digits and the sum of x and y has an even number of digits.  What is the number x?<n>Output: 0<n><n>Input: How many integers less than 2010 are not divisible by 8?<n>Output: 167<n><n>### Solution:<n><n>To count the number of Schnauer in the Doberman Puppy problem, <n><n>find the difference in the numbers and count that many number of <n><n>schnauzer to complete the equation. <n><n>Then count forward from the number of pups. <n><n><n>To count the total number of digits in the shadows, you have to count the number <n><n>of digits in the shadows divided by two. Since the answer is not an even number <n><n>therefore divide 1 by the digits number.<n><n>```python<n>#Counts the total number of digits<n>def countdigits(num):<n>    num1=str(num)<n>    return len(num1)<n><n># Count the total number of digits that are<n># even and subtract the number that are odd <n>def subEvenOdd(num):<n>    totalcount=0<n>    num1=num<n>    evenindex=[2]<n>    oddindex=[3,5,7]<n>    for i in range(0,len(num)):<n>        if evenindex.append(i)>0:<n>            totalcount+=1<n>            evenindex.pop()<n>            evenindex.append(int(num[i]))<n>        else:<n>            totalcount+=-1<n>    num=str(num)#change to string so can convert to int<n>    return totalcount<n><n>#Counts the digits in the number 60<n>ansnwer=countdigits(60)<n>print(ansnwer)<n>ans=subEvenOdd(ansnwer)#find the number of digits<n>print(ans)<n>```<n><n>### To count the number of Dobermans you need to keep track of the remaining dogs after each step <n><n>### to find the number of Dobermans you need to subtract the number of Dobermann from the total. Then take the remainder.<n><n>```python <n>d=3<n>n=20

The program should return the number of leap days in the given year.<n><n>Leap years have 366 days. They are years ending in a zero followed by a 2, 4, 6, 8, 0<n><n>### Solution:<n><n>import math<n>    <n>def leap_year(n):<n>    if n% 4 ==0:<n>        if n % 100== 0:<n>             return( math.ceil(n/4) == 4)<n>        else:<n>             return(1)<n>    return(0)<n><n><n>### Test 1:<n>    leap_year(2000)<n>### Test 2:<n><n>    leap_yea 2006<n>### Test 3:<n>    leapye 2018<n>### Test 4:<n>    leap yea 0<n>### Test 5:<n>    leap year 6<n>### Test5:<n>    leape year 6<n><n># leap_year(6000)<n><n><n><n><n><n>### Instruction: Answer the following code.<n><n>### <n>### Test 6:<n>    leap = 4  <n>### Test 7:<n>    leap= 2018  <n><n><n># leapeyear(2019)<n><n>

Therefore, the midpoint of the line lies on the x-axis, and must satisfy the equation x = -x, which has the unique solution x = 0. Therefore, y = 0.  The equation of the line is y = 0 -- (0,0,0) <n><n>Input: "28" + 20 * "25"<n>Output: 6825<n><n>Input:  a = 5/3;b = [((a / b) ^ 2) - a] * b;<n>Output: 1.96150713<n><n>Input: the number that is 0.7 times another number.<n>Output: 0 <n><n>Input: y = a; t = sqrt(2) * t; a = a * t; t = sqrt(-1) * t; a *= t;<n>Output: 4.24204814<n><n>*Input: y = x + y;<n>

This year, the average salary is 2222 krugerrands, which is 1086 krugerrands more than 10 times the average salary last year. How many krugerrands can the average salary be each year from now until the average salary is equal to 30000?<n># Solution: First, find the average salary over the 6 years and the difference between average salary at each year minus difference between the average salary the 2 years before. Then, sum the result of each year to find the missing average salary. This may be easier than solving it by iterative method.<n>def solutions(number):<n>    avg_over5_years = (0)<n>    for y in range(1, 5):<n>        avg = (sum(number[:y])/y)<n>        for x in range(y - 2):<n>            avg_over5 = (avg_over5_seconds + (sum(number[:x+1]) - sum(number[:x])))  <n>    def difference(s):<n>        def sloop(s, n):<n>            if n == 0:<n>                return 0<n>            n -= 1<n>            return n * (sloop(s, n-1))<n>        return sloop(s, x)    <n>    diff = difference(avg_over5)<n>    avg_number = (diff - sloop(diff,(y / 3)) )<n>    if (avg_number == '0') and (avg_number > 0):<n>        avg_number = 1<n>    return avg_number   <n><n><n>if __name__ == '__main__':<n>    number = [1000,1877,2554,3331,4018,4805]<n>    print(solutions(number))<n>

Choices:  A: serve food B: eat C: set table D: serve meal E: present bill<n>Output:		(choose) A or B<n><n><n>### Instruction:Write a method which takes an integer N and replaces each vowel letter A,E,I,O, and U with its position in the alphabet. So, if N is “abcd” your method should return “bcde”.<n><n>  Example:<n><n>Input:<n><n>N = 32<n><n>Output: 7<n><n><n>```<n>int find_vowel( char *word ) {<n>    // Write code...<n>    int vowels_found = 0;<n>    int i = 0;<n><n>    while (i < (sizeof(word) - 1)) {<n>        if(isupper(word[i]) || islower(word[i])) {<n>            vowels_found++;<n>            <n>        } if(isalpha(word[i])){<n>        vowels_found+=1;<n>       <n>        }<n>    i = i +1;<n>    }<n>    return vowels_found;<n>}<n>```

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Output: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Output: 36<n><n>Input: Sally picks 30 seashells on Monday. On Tuesday, she picks half as many seashells as she did on Monday. If she can sell each seashell for $1.20, how much money can she make if she sells all of her seashells?<n>Output: 54<n><n>Input: Jordan and Perry took a boat out to the lake to go fishing on a Monday morning. Choices:  A: pub B: plane C: beer D: store E: fraternity house<n>Output:		B: plane, beer, E: fraternity<n><n>Input: How old is Paul, If you subtract 7 from 3, plus 2 times 4, minus 12 plus 10 plus Paul's age, minus 10<n>Output: 16<n><n>Input: 36129<n>Output: 32525<n><n>### Solution:<n><n>For the first problem, let x be the number of Dobermans, so we have:<n><n>1. Five less than three times (x) plus the difference between (x) and (20) = 90<n><n>2. x - 5 = x20 + x - 10<n><n>We can now multiply each side by 30 and solve:<n><n>1. 15x - 5x = 90x + 20x - 10x<n><n>2. 4 = x<n><n>3. 35 = 30x<n><n>4. 7 = x<n><n>We want x to be Schnauzers. The number of Dobermans can be found by subtracting the number of Schnazurians<n><n>x = 35<n><n>Therefore, the number of Schnazzers is 55<n><n>For the second problem, we need to figure out the two values by which the number of toothbrushes was reduced if we know the number that were given away.<n><n>So we know that <n><n>g1 + g2 +... + g= 330<n><n>so<n><n>(g1 + g2) +... +(g29) = 330 since we subtracted 1 from g30<n><n>g1 = 53<n><n>g2 = 67<n><n>g30 = 5<n><n>Then we can reduce the values to solve for g29.<n><n>Subtracting the values, we get:<n><n>- 53 + 67 +... + 5 = 330<n>-.29<n><n>g29 = 324<n><n>(5 + 67) +... +.29 = 330 (using.29 instead of .25 to avoid losing a significant number with long addition)<n><n>So now, we know that g29

Choices:  A: gas stations B: city C: london D: train station E: airport<n>Output:		E<n><n>#!/bin/python3<n><n>import math<n>import sys<n><n>def findN(m, n, index, arr):<n>    # code<n>    #print(index-1)<n>    if(index-1 == 0):<n>        return sum(arr[0:m])<n>    if(index > 0 and index-1 > 0):<n>        sum1 = findN(m,n,index-1,arr)<n>        sum2 = findN(m,n,index-1,arr)<n>        sum3 = findN(m,(n-m),index-1,arr[:])<n>        sum4 = findN(m-int(n/2),m,index-1,arr[int(n/2):])<n>        sum = sum1 + sum2 + sum3 + sum4<n>        return sum<n>    else:<n>        #print(sum1)<n>        return sum(range(index-1,index))<n><n>if __name__ == "__main__":<n>    testcases = int(input())<n>    for i in range(0,testcases):<n>        N = int(input()) # number of test cases<n>        m = int(input()) #[lenth]<n>        n = int(input()) [length]<n>        arr = list(map(int,input().split()))<n>        #index1 = int(input())[index for each test]<n>        <n>        for a1 in range (0,N):<n>            print(findN(m,n, a1, arr))<n><n>

How long are the shadows from the building 6 hours past noon in inches?<n>Output: 360<n><n>Input:What is a great, but non-specific, overall benefit of exercise? However, this does not prove that none of the other dogs have more legs than the total number of legs in this group.<n>-If the total number of legs is greater than the number you calculated, then it’s guaranteed that either all or none of the dogs in the group have more than two legs.<n><n>### Input: Four more than two times the number of cats is equal to 18 plus 3. From there the program will ask the user if "the number is the sum of a number and the remainder of the number" if so the program will ask the remainder and after each number the program will decrease the remainder by one until the remainder becomes 0.  <n>#Notes: For example: If the user enters the number 9 the program will say "Is the number the sum of a number?" if so the answer is yes and then the program will have the user tell "what is the remainder after subtracting the number for that number" if the user says the remainder of the number is 4 the program will say "how about 5 and subtract 1 from the remainder" <n>#Note: if after every number the user enters, the number minus the remainder is 0 or less than zero the user will say the remainder is 0. If not, the user will say the number minus the remainder still has a remainder, and the program will ask the rest until the remainder becomes zero.  <n><n>def run(number1, number2, remainder):<n>	total = number2<n><n>	number = 0<n>	for number in number2:<n>		runno = True <n>		while runno ==True:<n>			if total == number:<n>				total = total - number<n>			else:<n>			runno = False<n>		<n>		if remainder == 0:<n>			return "Yes"<n>		if remainder > 0:<n>	<n>			remainder = remainder - 1<n>############<n>#Author: Adam sweet (AdamSweet45.com)<n>################################<n>#input: a letter and a number between 0 and 9<n>#output: a "word" with the same spelled and a letter added for each occurrence of the letter in the word. For example, the word "word"

How many times does the realistic optimist sing during the ride?<n>Output: (313501)<n><n><!-- --><n><n>#### Solution<n><n>##### First Question:<n><n>> Answer: (C)<n>This is my favorite question so far because it is so simple and so beautifully done.<n>This question is asking the the difference between `n` and `(n-3)` is 90.<n>The solution is obviously that there are a total of 90 less schnauzers which makes it 55 total.<n><n>##### Second Question:<n><n>>Answer: (E)<n>This question might be the hardest question I've seen yet. (every hour past noon a shadows from a building stretches 5 feet longer starting at 0 noon)<n><n>>Each of these questions, if you've read them carefully, is asking the same thing;<n><n>>How many of each type of item is left from the beginning?<n><n>>There are several methods to solve this kind of problem.<n><n><n>I use one that is a little different everytime and I write it down every time it works.
